Solvent accessibility might be calculated for the backbone, sidechain and total (backbone plus sidechain).

operation_1821.name: Protein residue surface calculation (accessible molecular)
operation_1821.definition:
Calculate the solvent accessibility ('accessible molecular surface') for each residue in a structure.
Solvent accessibility might be calculated for the backbone, sidechain and total (backbone plus sidechain).

operation_1822.name: Protein residue surface calculation (vacuum molecular)
operation_1822.definition:
Calculate the solvent accessibility ('vacuum molecular surface') for each residue in a structure. This is the accessibility of the residue when taken out of the protein together with the backbone atoms of any residue it is covalently bound to.
Solvent accessibility might be calculated for the backbone, sidechain and total (backbone plus sidechain).

operation_1823.name: Protein surface calculation (accessible molecular)
operation_1823.definition: Calculate the solvent accessibility ('accessible molecular surface') for a structure as a whole.

operation_1824.name: Protein surface calculation (accessible)
operation_1824.definition: Calculate the solvent accessibility ('accessible surface') for a structure as a whole.

operation_1825.name: Backbone torsion angle calculation
operation_1825.definition: Calculate for each residue in a protein structure all its backbone torsion angles.

operation_1826.name: Full torsion angle calculation
operation_1826.definition: Calculate for each residue in a protein structure all its torsion angles.

operation_1827.name: Cysteine torsion angle calculation
operation_1827.definition: Calculate for each cysteine (bridge) all its torsion angles.

operation_1828.name: Tau angle calculation
operation_1828.definition:
For each amino acid in a protein structure calculate the backbone angle tau.
Tau is the backbone angle N-Calpha-C (angle over the C-alpha).

operation_1829.name: Cysteine bridge detection
operation_1829.definition: Detect cysteine bridges (from coordinate data) in a protein structure.

operation_1830.name: Free cysteine detection
operation_1830.definition:
Detect free cysteines in a protein structure.
A free cysteine is neither involved in a cysteine bridge, nor functions as a ligand to a metal.

operation_1831.name: Metal-bound cysteine detection
operation_1831.definition: Detect cysteines that are bound to metal in a protein structure.

operation_1832.name: Residue contact calculation (residue-nucleic acid)
operation_1832.definition: Calculate protein residue contacts with nucleic acids in a structure.

operation_1834.name: Protein-metal contact calculation
operation_1834.definition: Calculate protein residue contacts with metal in a structure.

operation_1835.name: Residue contact calculation (residue-negative ion)
operation_1835.definition: Calculate ion contacts in a structure (all ions for all side chain atoms).

operation_1836.name: Residue bump detection
operation_1836.definition: Detect 'bumps' between residues in a structure, i.e. those with pairs of atoms whose Van der Waals' radii interpenetrate more than a defined distance.

operation_1837.name: Residue symmetry contact calculation
operation_1837.definition:
Calculate the number of symmetry contacts made by residues in a protein structure.
A symmetry contact is a contact between two atoms in different asymmetric unit.

operation_1838.name: Residue contact calculation (residue-ligand)
operation_1838.definition: Calculate contacts between residues and ligands in a protein structure.

operation_1839.name: Salt bridge calculation
operation_1839.definition:
Calculate (and possibly score) salt bridges in a protein structure.
Salt bridges are interactions between oppositely charged atoms in different residues. The output might include the inter-atomic distance.

operation_1841.name: Rotamer likelihood prediction
operation_1841.definition:
Predict rotamer likelihoods for all 20 amino acid types at each position in a protein structure.
Output typically includes, for each residue position, the likelihoods for the 20 amino acid types with estimated reliability of the 20 likelihoods.

operation_1842.name: Proline mutation value calculation
operation_1842.definition: Calculate for each position in a protein structure the chance that a proline, when introduced at this position, would increase the stability of the whole protein.

operation_1843.name: Residue packing validation
operation_1843.definition: Identify poorly packed residues in protein structures.

operation_1844.name: Protein geometry validation
operation_1844.definition: Validate protein geometry, for example bond lengths, bond angles, torsion angles, chiralities, planaraties etc.  An example is validation of a Ramachandran plot of a protein structure.

operation_1845.name: PDB file sequence retrieval
operation_1845.definition: Extract a molecular sequence from a PDB file.

operation_1846.name: HET group detection
operation_1846.definition:
Identify HET groups in PDB files.
A HET group usually corresponds to ligands, lipids, but might also (not consistently) include groups that are attached to amino acids. Each HET group is supposed to have a unique three letter code and a unique name which might be given in the output.

operation_1847.name: DSSP secondary structure assignment
operation_1847.definition: Determine for residue the DSSP determined secondary structure in three-state (HSC).

operation_1848.name: Structure formatting
operation_1848.definition: Reformat (a file or other report of) tertiary structure data.

operation_1850.name: Protein cysteine and disulfide bond assignment
operation_1850.definition: Assign cysteine bonding state and disulfide bond partners in protein structures.

operation_1913.name: Residue validation
operation_1913.definition: Identify poor quality amino acid positions in protein structures.

operation_1914.name: Structure retrieval (water)
operation_1914.definition: Query a tertiary structure database and retrieve water molecules.

operation_2008.name: siRNA duplex prediction
operation_2008.definition: Identify or predict siRNA duplexes in RNA.

operation_2120.name: Listfile processing
operation_2120.definition: Process an EMBOSS listfile (list of EMBOSS Uniform Sequence Addresses).

operation_2121.name: Sequence file editing
operation_2121.definition: Perform basic (non-analytical) operations on a report or file of sequences (which might include features), such as file concatenation, removal or ordering of sequences, creation of subset or a new file of sequences.

operation_2122.name: Sequence alignment file processing
operation_2122.definition: Perform basic (non-analytical) operations on a sequence alignment file, such as copying or removal and ordering of sequences.

operation_2123.name: Small molecule data processing
operation_2123.definition: Process (read and / or write) physicochemical property data for small molecules.

operation_2222.name: Data retrieval (ontology annotation)
operation_2222.definition: Search and retrieve documentation on a bioinformatics ontology.

operation_2224.name: Data retrieval (ontology concept)
operation_2224.definition: Query an ontology and retrieve concepts or relations.

operation_2233.name: Representative sequence identification
operation_2233.definition: Identify a representative sequence from a set of sequences, typically using scores from pair-wise alignment or other comparison of the sequences.

operation_2234.name: Structure file processing
operation_2234.definition: Perform basic (non-analytical) operations on a file of molecular tertiary structural data.

operation_2237.name: Data retrieval (sequence profile)
operation_2237.definition:
Query a profile data resource and retrieve one or more profile(s) and / or associated annotation.
This includes direct retrieval methods that retrieve a profile by, e.g. the profile name.

operation_2238.name: Statistical calculation
operation_2238.definition: Perform a statistical data operation of some type, e.g. calibration or validation.

operation_2239.name: 3D-1D scoring matrix generation
operation_2239.definition:
Calculate a 3D-1D scoring matrix from analysis of protein sequence and structural data.
A 3D-1D scoring matrix scores the probability of amino acids occurring in different structural environments.

operation_2241.name: Transmembrane protein visualisation
operation_2241.definition: Visualise transmembrane proteins, typically the transmembrane regions within a sequence.

operation_2246.name: Demonstration
operation_2246.definition: An operation performing purely illustrative (pedagogical) purposes.

operation_2264.name: Data retrieval (pathway or network)
operation_2264.definition: Query a biological pathways database and retrieve annotation on one or more pathways.

operation_2265.name: Data retrieval (identifier)
operation_2265.definition: Query a database and retrieve one or more data identifiers.

operation_2284.name: Nucleic acid density plotting
operation_2284.definition: Calculate a density plot (of base composition) for a nucleotide sequence.

operation_2403.name: Sequence analysis
operation_2403.definition: Analyse one or more known molecular sequences.

operation_2405.name: Protein interaction data processing
operation_2405.definition: Process (read and / or write) protein interaction data.

operation_2407.name: Annotation processing
operation_2407.definition: Process (read and / or write) annotation of some type, typically annotation on an entry from a biological or biomedical database entity.

operation_2409.name: Data handling
operation_2409.definition: Basic (non-analytical) operations of some data, either a file or equivalent entity in memory, such that the same basic type of data is consumed as input and generated as output.

operation_2410.name: Gene expression analysis
operation_2410.definition: Analyse gene expression and regulation data.

operation_2411.name: Structural profile processing
operation_2411.definition: Process (read and / or write) one or more structural (3D) profile(s) or template(s) of some type.

operation_2412.name: Data index processing
operation_2412.definition: Process (read and / or write) an index of (typically a file of) biological data.

operation_2413.name: Sequence profile processing
operation_2413.definition: Process (read and / or write) some type of sequence profile.

operation_2414.name: Protein function analysis
operation_2414.definition: Analyse protein function, typically by processing protein sequence and/or structural data, and generate an informative report.

operation_2415.name: Protein folding analysis
operation_2415.definition: Analyse, simulate or predict protein folding, typically by processing sequence and / or structural data.  For example, predict sites of nucleation or stabilisation key to protein folding.

operation_2417.name: Physicochemical property data processing
operation_2417.definition: Process (read and / or write) data on the physicochemical property of a molecule.

operation_2420.name: Operation (typed)
operation_2420.definition: Process (read and / or write) data of a specific type, for example applying analytical methods.

operation_2421.name: Database search
operation_2421.definition:
Search a database (or other data resource) with a supplied query and retrieve entries (or parts of entries) that are similar to the query.
Typically the query is compared to each entry and high scoring matches (hits) are returned. For example, a BLAST search of a sequence database.

operation_2422.name: Data retrieval
operation_2422.definition: Retrieve an entry (or part of an entry) from a data resource that matches a supplied query. This might include some primary data and annotation. The query is a data identifier or other indexed term. For example, retrieve a sequence record with the specified accession number, or matching supplied keywords.

operation_2423.name: Prediction and recognition
operation_2423.definition: Predict, recognise, detect or identify some properties of a biomolecule.

operation_2424.name: Comparison
operation_2424.definition: Compare two or more things to identify similarities.

operation_2425.name: Optimisation and refinement
operation_2425.definition: Refine or optimise some data model.

operation_2426.name: Modelling and simulation
operation_2426.definition: Model or simulate some biological entity or system, typically using mathematical techniques including  dynamical systems, statistical models, differential equations, and game theoretic models.

operation_2427.name: Data handling
operation_2427.definition: Perform basic operations on some data or a database.

operation_2429.name: Mapping
operation_2429.definition: Map properties to positions on an biological entity (typically a molecular sequence or structure), or assemble such an entity from constituent parts.

operation_2430.name: Design
operation_2430.definition: Design a biological entity (typically a molecular sequence or structure) with specific properties.

operation_2432.name: Microarray data processing
operation_2432.definition: Process (read and / or write) microarray data.

operation_2433.name: Codon usage table processing
operation_2433.definition: Process (read and / or write) a codon usage table.

operation_2434.name: Data retrieval (codon usage table)
operation_2434.definition: Retrieve a codon usage table and / or associated annotation.

operation_2435.name: Gene expression profile processing
operation_2435.definition: Process (read and / or write) a gene expression profile.

operation_2436.name: Gene-set enrichment analysis
operation_2436.definition:
Identify classes of genes or proteins that are over or under-represented in a large set of genes or proteins.  For example analysis of a set of genes corresponding to a gene expression profile, annotated with Gene Ontology (GO) concepts, where eventual over-/under-representation of certain GO concept within the studied set of genes is revealed.
The Gene Ontology (GO) is typically used, the input is a set of Gene IDs, and the output of the analysis is typically a ranked list of GO concepts, each associated with a p-value.
"Gene set analysis" (often used interchangeably or in an overlapping sense with "gene-set enrichment analysis") refers to the functional analysis (term enrichment) of a differentially expressed set of genes, rather than all genes analysed.

operation_2437.name: Gene regulatory network prediction
operation_2437.definition: Predict a network of gene regulation.

operation_2438.name: Pathway or network processing
operation_2438.definition: Generate, analyse or handle a biological pathway or network.

operation_2439.name: RNA secondary structure analysis
operation_2439.definition: Process (read and / or write) RNA secondary structure data.

operation_2440.name: Structure processing (RNA)
operation_2440.definition: Process (read and / or write) RNA tertiary structure data.

operation_2443.name: Phylogenetic tree processing
operation_2443.definition: Generate, process or analyse phylogenetic tree or trees.

operation_2444.name: Protein secondary structure processing
operation_2444.definition: Process (read and / or write) protein secondary structure data.

operation_2445.name: Protein interaction network processing
operation_2445.definition: Process (read and / or write) a network of protein interactions.

operation_2446.name: Sequence processing
operation_2446.definition: Process (read and / or write) one or more molecular sequences and associated annotation.

operation_2447.name: Sequence processing (protein)
operation_2447.definition: Process (read and / or write) a protein sequence and associated annotation.

operation_2448.name: Sequence processing (nucleic acid)
operation_2448.definition: Process (read and / or write) a nucleotide sequence and associated annotation.

operation_2451.name: Sequence comparison
operation_2451.definition: Compare two or more molecular sequences.

operation_2452.name: Sequence cluster processing
operation_2452.definition: Process (read and / or write) a sequence cluster.

operation_2453.name: Feature table processing
operation_2453.definition: Process (read and / or write) a sequence feature table.

operation_2454.name: Gene prediction
operation_2454.definition:
Detect, predict and identify genes or components of genes in DNA sequences, including promoters, coding regions, splice sites, etc.
Methods for gene prediction might be ab initio, based on phylogenetic comparisons, use motifs, sequence features, support vector machine, alignment etc.

operation_2456.name: GPCR classification
operation_2456.definition: Classify G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) into families and subfamilies.

operation_2457.name: GPCR coupling selectivity prediction
operation_2457.definition: Predict G-protein coupled receptor (GPCR) coupling selectivity.

operation_2459.name: Structure processing (protein)
operation_2459.definition: Process (read and / or write) a protein tertiary structure.

operation_2460.name: Protein atom surface calculation
operation_2460.definition:
Calculate the solvent accessibility for each atom in a structure.
Waters are not considered.

operation_2461.name: Protein residue surface calculation
operation_2461.definition: Calculate the solvent accessibility for each residue in a structure.

operation_2462.name: Protein surface calculation
operation_2462.definition: Calculate the solvent accessibility of a structure as a whole.

operation_2463.name: Sequence alignment processing
operation_2463.definition: Process (read and / or write) a molecular sequence alignment.

operation_2464.name: Protein-protein binding site prediction
operation_2464.definition: Identify or predict protein-protein binding sites.

operation_2465.name: Structure processing
operation_2465.definition: Process (read and / or write) a molecular tertiary structure.

operation_2466.name: Map annotation
operation_2466.definition: Annotate a DNA map of some type with terms from a controlled vocabulary.

operation_2468.name: Data retrieval (phylogenetic tree)
operation_2468.definition: Retrieve a phylogenetic tree from a data resource.

operation_2469.name: Data retrieval (protein interaction annotation)
operation_2469.definition: Retrieve information on a protein interaction.

operation_2470.name: Data retrieval (protein family annotation)
operation_2470.definition: Retrieve information on a protein family.

operation_2471.name: Data retrieval (RNA family annotation)
operation_2471.definition: Retrieve information on an RNA family.

operation_2472.name: Data retrieval (gene annotation)
operation_2472.definition: Retrieve information on a specific gene.

operation_2473.name: Data retrieval (genotype and phenotype annotation)
operation_2473.definition: Retrieve information on a specific genotype or phenotype.

operation_2474.name: Protein architecture comparison
operation_2474.definition: Compare the architecture of two or more protein structures.

operation_2475.name: Protein architecture recognition
operation_2475.definition:
Identify the architecture of a protein structure.
Includes methods that try to suggest the most likely biological unit for a given protein X-ray crystal structure based on crystal symmetry and scoring of putative protein-protein interfaces.

operation_2476.name: Molecular dynamics
operation_2476.definition: The simulation of molecular (typically protein) conformation using a computational model of physical forces and computer simulation.

operation_2478.name: Nucleic acid sequence analysis
operation_2478.definition: Analyse a nucleic acid sequence (using methods that are only applicable to nucleic acid sequences).

operation_2479.name: Protein sequence analysis
operation_2479.definition: Analyse a protein sequence (using methods that are only applicable to protein sequences).

operation_2481.name: Nucleic acid structure analysis
operation_2481.definition: Analyse nucleic acid tertiary structural data.

operation_2482.name: Secondary structure processing
operation_2482.definition: Process (read and / or write) a molecular secondary structure.

operation_2483.name: Structure comparison
operation_2483.definition: Compare two or more molecular tertiary structures.

operation_2485.name: Helical wheel drawing
operation_2485.definition: Render a helical wheel representation of protein secondary structure.

operation_2486.name: Topology diagram drawing
operation_2486.definition: Render a topology diagram of protein secondary structure.

operation_2487.name: Protein structure comparison
operation_2487.definition:
Compare protein tertiary structures.
Methods might identify structural neighbors, find structural similarities or define a structural core.

operation_2489.name: Subcellular localisation prediction
operation_2489.definition:
Predict the subcellular localisation of a protein sequence.
The prediction might include subcellular localisation (nuclear, cytoplasmic, mitochondrial, chloroplast, plastid, membrane etc) or export (extracellular proteins) of a protein.

operation_2490.name: Residue contact calculation (residue-residue)
operation_2490.definition: Calculate contacts between residues in a protein structure.

operation_2491.name: Hydrogen bond calculation (inter-residue)
operation_2491.definition: Identify potential hydrogen bonds between amino acid residues.

operation_2492.name: Protein interaction prediction
operation_2492.definition: Predict the interactions of proteins with other proteins.

operation_2493.name: Codon usage data processing
operation_2493.definition: Process (read and / or write) codon usage data.

operation_2495.name: Expression analysis
operation_2495.definition: Process (read and/or write) expression data from experiments measuring molecules (e.g. omics data), including analysis of one or more expression profiles, typically to interpret them in functional terms.

operation_2496.name: Gene regulatory network processing
operation_2496.definition: Process (read and / or write) a network of gene regulation.

operation_2497.name: Pathway or network analysis
operation_2497.definition: Generate, process or analyse a biological pathway or network.

operation_2498.name: Sequencing-based expression profile data analysis
operation_2498.definition: Analyse SAGE, MPSS or SBS experimental data, typically to identify or quantify mRNA transcripts.

operation_2499.name: Splicing analysis
operation_2499.definition: Predict, analyse, characterize or model splice sites, splicing events and so on, typically by comparing multiple nucleic acid sequences.

operation_2501.name: Nucleic acid analysis
operation_2501.definition: Process (read and / or write) nucleic acid sequence or structural data.

operation_2502.name: Protein analysis
operation_2502.definition: Process (read and / or write) protein sequence or structural data.

operation_2503.name: Sequence data processing
operation_2503.definition: Process (read and / or write) molecular sequence data.

operation_2504.name: Structural data processing
operation_2504.definition: Process (read and / or write) molecular structural data.

operation_2506.name: Protein sequence alignment analysis
operation_2506.definition: Analyse a protein sequence alignment, typically to detect features or make predictions.

operation_2507.name: Nucleic acid sequence alignment analysis
operation_2507.definition: Analyse a protein sequence alignment, typically to detect features or make predictions.

operation_2508.name: Nucleic acid sequence comparison
operation_2508.definition: Compare two or more nucleic acid sequences.

operation_2509.name: Protein sequence comparison
operation_2509.definition: Compare two or more protein sequences.

operation_2510.name: DNA back-translation
operation_2510.definition: Back-translate a protein sequence into DNA.

operation_2511.name: Sequence editing (nucleic acid)
operation_2511.definition: Edit or change a nucleic acid sequence, either randomly or specifically.

operation_2512.name: Sequence editing (protein)
operation_2512.definition: Edit or change a protein sequence, either randomly or specifically.

operation_2513.name: Sequence generation (nucleic acid)
operation_2513.definition: Generate a nucleic acid sequence by some means.

operation_2514.name: Sequence generation (protein)
operation_2514.definition: Generate a protein sequence by some means.

operation_2515.name: Nucleic acid sequence visualisation
operation_2515.definition:
Visualise, format or render a nucleic acid sequence.
Various nucleic acid sequence analysis methods might generate a sequence rendering but are not (for brevity) listed under here.

operation_2516.name: Protein sequence visualisation
operation_2516.definition:
Visualise, format or render a protein sequence.
Various protein sequence analysis methods might generate a sequence rendering but are not (for brevity) listed under here.

operation_2519.name: Structure processing (nucleic acid)
operation_2519.definition:
Process (read and / or write) nucleic acid tertiary structure data.
http://edamontology.org/operation_2481

operation_2520.name: DNA mapping
operation_2520.definition: Generate a map of a DNA sequence annotated with positional or non-positional features of some type.

operation_2521.name: Map data processing
operation_2521.definition: Process (read and / or write) a DNA map of some type.

operation_2574.name: Protein hydropathy calculation
operation_2574.definition: Analyse the hydrophobic, hydrophilic or charge properties of a protein (from analysis of sequence or structural information).

operation_2575.name: Binding site prediction
operation_2575.definition: Identify or predict catalytic residues, active sites or other ligand-binding sites in protein sequences or structures.

operation_2844.name: Structure clustering
operation_2844.definition: Build clusters of similar structures, typically using scores from structural alignment methods.

operation_2871.name: Sequence tagged site (STS) mapping
operation_2871.definition:
Generate a physical DNA map (sequence map) from analysis of sequence tagged sites (STS).
An STS is a short subsequence of known sequence and location that occurs only once in the chromosome or genome that is being mapped. Sources of STSs include 1. expressed sequence tags (ESTs), simple sequence length polymorphisms (SSLPs), and random genomic sequences from cloned genomic DNA or database sequences.

operation_2928.name: Alignment
operation_2928.definition: Compare two or more entities, typically the sequence or structure (or derivatives) of macromolecules, to identify equivalent subunits.

operation_2929.name: Protein fragment weight comparison
operation_2929.definition: Calculate the molecular weight of a protein (or fragments) and compare it to another protein or reference data. Generally used for protein identification.

operation_2930.name: Protein property comparison
operation_2930.definition: Compare the physicochemical properties of two or more proteins (or reference data).

operation_2931.name: Secondary structure comparison
operation_2931.definition: Compare two or more molecular secondary structures.

operation_2932.name: Hopp and Woods plotting
operation_2932.definition: Generate a Hopp and Woods plot of antigenicity of a protein.

operation_2934.name: Cluster textual view generation
operation_2934.definition: Generate a view of clustered quantitative data, annotated with textual information.

operation_2935.name: Clustering profile plotting
operation_2935.definition: Visualise clustered quantitative data as set of different profiles, where each profile is plotted versus different entities or samples on the X-axis.

operation_2936.name: Dendrograph plotting
operation_2936.definition: Generate a dendrograph of raw, preprocessed or clustered expression (e.g. microarray) data.

operation_2937.name: Proximity map plotting
operation_2937.definition: Generate a plot of distances (distance or correlation matrix) between expression values.

operation_2938.name: Dendrogram visualisation
operation_2938.definition: Visualise clustered expression data using a tree diagram.
synonyms: Expression data tree or dendrogram rendering

operation_2939.name: Principal component visualisation
operation_2939.definition:
Visualize the results of a principal component analysis (orthogonal data transformation).  For example, visualization of the principal components (essential subspace) coming from a Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on the trajectory atomistic coordinates of a molecular structure.
The use of Principal Component Analysis (PCA), a multivariate statistical analysis to obtain collective variables on the atomic positional fluctuations, helps to separate the configurational space in two subspaces: an essential subspace containing relevant motions, and another one containing irrelevant local fluctuations.

operation_2940.name: Scatter plot plotting
operation_2940.definition: Render a graph in which the values of two variables are plotted along two axes; the pattern of the points reveals any correlation.

operation_2941.name: Whole microarray graph plotting
operation_2941.definition: Visualise gene expression data where each band (or line graph) corresponds to a sample.

operation_2942.name: Treemap visualisation
operation_2942.definition: Visualise gene expression data after hierarchical clustering for representing hierarchical relationships.

operation_2943.name: Box-Whisker plot plotting
operation_2943.definition: Generate a box plot, i.e. a depiction of groups of numerical data through their quartiles.

operation_2944.name: Physical mapping
operation_2944.definition: Generate a physical (sequence) map of a DNA sequence showing the physical distance (base pairs) between features or landmarks such as restriction sites, cloned DNA fragments, genes and other genetic markers.

operation_2945.name: Analysis
operation_2945.definition:
Apply analytical methods to existing data of a specific type.
This excludes non-analytical methods that read and write the same basic type of data (for that, see 'Data handling').

operation_2946.name: Alignment analysis
operation_2946.definition: Process or analyse an alignment of molecular sequences or structures.

operation_2947.name: Article analysis
operation_2947.definition: Analyse a body of scientific text (typically a full text article from a scientific journal.)

operation_2948.name: Molecular interaction analysis
operation_2948.definition: Analyse the interactions of two or more molecules (or parts of molecules) that are known to interact.

operation_2949.name: Protein-protein interaction analysis
operation_2949.definition: Analyse the interactions of proteins with other proteins.

operation_2950.name: Residue distance calculation
operation_2950.definition:
Calculate contacts between residues, or between residues and other groups, in a protein structure, on the basis of distance calculations.
This includes identifying HET groups, which usually correspond to ligands, lipids, but might also (not consistently) include groups that are attached to amino acids. Each HET group is supposed to have a unique three letter code and a unique name which might be given in the output.  It can also include calculation of symmetry contacts, i.e. a contact between two atoms in different asymmetric unit.

operation_2951.name: Alignment processing
operation_2951.definition: Process (read and / or write) an alignment of two or more molecular sequences, structures or derived data.

operation_2952.name: Structure alignment processing
operation_2952.definition: Process (read and / or write) a molecular tertiary (3D) structure alignment.

operation_2962.name: Codon usage bias calculation
operation_2962.definition: Calculate codon usage bias, e.g. generate a codon usage bias plot.

operation_2963.name: Codon usage bias plotting
operation_2963.definition: Generate a codon usage bias plot.

operation_2964.name: Codon usage fraction calculation
operation_2964.definition: Calculate the differences in codon usage fractions between two sequences, sets of sequences, codon usage tables etc.

operation_2990.name: Classification
operation_2990.definition: Assign molecular sequences, structures or other biological data to a specific group or category according to qualities it shares with that group or category.

operation_2993.name: Molecular interaction data processing
operation_2993.definition: Process (read and / or write) molecular interaction data.

operation_2995.name: Sequence classification
operation_2995.definition: Assign molecular sequence(s) to a group or category.

operation_2996.name: Structure classification
operation_2996.definition: Assign molecular structure(s) to a group or category.

operation_2997.name: Protein comparison
operation_2997.definition: Compare two or more proteins (or some aspect) to identify similarities.

operation_2998.name: Nucleic acid comparison
operation_2998.definition: Compare two or more nucleic acids to identify similarities.

operation_3023.name: Prediction and recognition (protein)
operation_3023.definition: Predict, recognise, detect or identify some properties of proteins.

operation_3024.name: Prediction and recognition (nucleic acid)
operation_3024.definition: Predict, recognise, detect or identify some properties of nucleic acids.

operation_3080.name: Structure editing
operation_3080.definition: Edit, convert or otherwise change a  molecular tertiary structure, either randomly or specifically.

operation_3081.name: Sequence alignment editing
operation_3081.definition: Edit, convert or otherwise change a molecular sequence alignment, either randomly or specifically.

operation_3083.name: Pathway or network visualisation
operation_3083.definition: Render (visualise) a biological pathway or network.

operation_3084.name: Protein function prediction (from sequence)
operation_3084.definition:
Predict general (non-positional) functional properties of a protein from analysing its sequence.
For functional properties that are positional, use 'Protein site detection' instead.

operation_3087.name: Protein sequence feature detection
operation_3087.definition: Predict, recognise and identify functional or other key sites within protein sequences, typically by scanning for known motifs, patterns and regular expressions.

operation_3088.name: Protein property calculation (from sequence)
operation_3088.definition: Calculate (or predict) physical or chemical properties of a protein, including any non-positional properties of the molecular sequence, from processing a protein sequence.

operation_3090.name: Protein feature prediction (from structure)
operation_3090.definition: Predict, recognise and identify positional features in proteins from analysing protein structure.

operation_3092.name: Protein feature detection
operation_3092.definition:
Predict, recognise and identify positional features in proteins from analysing protein sequences or structures.
Features includes functional sites or regions, secondary structure, structural domains and so on. Methods might use fingerprints, motifs, profiles, hidden Markov models, sequence alignment etc to provide a mapping of a query protein sequence to a discriminatory element. This includes methods that search a secondary protein database (Prosite, Blocks, ProDom, Prints, Pfam etc.) to assign a protein sequence(s) to a known protein family or group.

operation_3093.name: Database search (by sequence)
operation_3093.definition: Screen a molecular sequence(s) against a database (of some type) to identify similarities between the sequence and database entries.

operation_3094.name: Protein interaction network prediction
operation_3094.definition: Predict a network of protein interactions.

operation_3095.name: Nucleic acid design
operation_3095.definition: Design (or predict) nucleic acid sequences with specific chemical or physical properties.

operation_3096.name: Editing
operation_3096.definition: Edit a data entity, either randomly or specifically.

operation_3180.name: Sequence assembly validation
operation_3180.definition: Evaluate a DNA sequence assembly, typically for purposes of quality control.

operation_3182.name: Genome alignment
operation_3182.definition: Align two or more (tpyically huge) molecular sequences that represent genomes.

operation_3183.name: Localised reassembly
operation_3183.definition: Reconstruction of a sequence assembly in a localised area.

operation_3184.name: Sequence assembly visualisation
operation_3184.definition: Render and visualise a DNA sequence assembly.

operation_3185.name: Base-calling
operation_3185.definition: Identify base (nucleobase) sequence from a fluorescence 'trace' data generated by an automated DNA sequencer.

operation_3186.name: Bisulfite mapping
operation_3186.definition:
The mapping of methylation sites in a DNA (genome) sequence.  Typically, the mapping of high-throughput bisulfite reads to the reference genome.
Bisulfite mapping follows high-throughput sequencing of DNA which has undergone bisulfite treatment followed by PCR amplification; unmethylated cytosines are specifically converted to thymine, allowing the methylation status of cytosine in the DNA to be detected.

operation_3187.name: Sequence contamination filtering
operation_3187.definition: Identify and filter a (typically large) sequence data set to remove sequences from contaminants in the sample that was sequenced.

operation_3189.name: Trim ends
operation_3189.definition:
Trim sequences (typically from an automated DNA sequencer) to remove misleading ends.
For example trim polyA tails, introns and primer sequence flanking the sequence of amplified exons, or other unwanted sequence.

operation_3190.name: Trim vector
operation_3190.definition: Trim sequences (typically from an automated DNA sequencer) to remove sequence-specific end regions, typically contamination from vector sequences.

operation_3191.name: Trim to reference
operation_3191.definition: Trim sequences (typically from an automated DNA sequencer) to remove the sequence ends that extend beyond an assembled reference sequence.

operation_3192.name: Sequence trimming
operation_3192.definition:
Cut (remove) the end from a molecular sequence.
This includes ennd trimming Trim sequences (typically from an automated DNA sequencer) to remove misleading ends. For example trim polyA tails, introns and primer sequence flanking the sequence of amplified exons, or other unwanted sequence. trimming to a reference sequence, Trim sequences (typically from an automated DNA sequencer) to remove the sequence ends that extend beyond an assembled reference sequence. vector trimming Trim sequences (typically from an automated DNA sequencer) to remove sequence-specific end regions, typically contamination from vector sequences.

operation_3194.name: Genome feature comparison
operation_3194.definition:
Compare the features of two genome sequences.
Genomic elements that might be compared include genes, indels, single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs), retrotransposons, tandem repeats and so on.

operation_3195.name: Sequencing error detection
operation_3195.definition: Detect errors in DNA sequences generated from sequencing projects).

operation_3196.name: Genotyping
operation_3196.definition:
Analyse DNA sequence data to identify differences between the genetic composition (genotype) of an individual compared to other individual's or a reference sequence.
Methods might consider cytogenetic analyses, copy number polymorphism (and calculate copy number calls for copy-number variation(CNV) regions), single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP), , rare copy number variation (CNV) identification, loss of heterozygosity data and so on.

operation_3197.name: Genetic variation analysis
operation_3197.definition:
Analyse a genetic variation, for example to annotate its location, alleles, classification, and effects on individual transcripts predicted for a gene model.
Genetic variation annotation provides contextual interpretation of coding SNP consequences in transcripts. It allows comparisons to be made between variation data in different populations or strains for the same transcript.

operation_3198.name: Read mapping
operation_3198.definition:
Align short oligonucleotide sequences (reads) to a larger (genomic) sequence.
The purpose of read mapping is to identify the location of sequenced fragments within a reference genome and assumes that there is, in fact, at least local similarity between the fragment and reference sequences.

operation_3199.name: Split read mapping
operation_3199.definition: A varient of oligonucleotide mapping where a read is mapped to two separate locations because of possible structural variation.

operation_3200.name: DNA barcoding
operation_3200.definition: Analyse DNA sequences in order to identify a DNA 'barcode'; marker genes or any short fragment(s) of DNA that are useful to diagnose the taxa of biological organisms.

operation_3201.name: SNP calling
operation_3201.definition: Identify single nucleotide change in base positions in sequencing data that differ from a reference genome and which might, especially by reference to population frequency or functional data, indicate a polymorphism.

operation_3202.name: Polymorphism detection
operation_3202.definition: Detect mutations in multiple DNA sequences, for example, from the alignment and comparison of the fluorescent traces produced by DNA sequencing hardware.

operation_3203.name: Chromatogram visualisation
operation_3203.definition: Visualise, format or render an image of a Chromatogram.

operation_3204.name: Methylation analysis
operation_3204.definition: Analyse cytosine methylation states in nucleic acid sequences.

operation_3205.name: Methylation calling
operation_3205.definition: Determine cytosine methylation status of specific positions in a nucleic acid sequences.

operation_3206.name: Whole genome methylation analysis
operation_3206.definition: Measure the overall level of methyl cytosines in a genome from analysis of experimental data, typically from chromatographic methods and methyl accepting capacity assay.

operation_3207.name: Gene methylation analysis
operation_3207.definition: Analysing the DNA methylation of specific genes or regions of interest.

operation_3208.name: Genome visualisation
operation_3208.definition: Visualise, format or render a nucleic acid sequence that is part of (and in context of) a complete genome sequence.

operation_3209.name: Genome comparison
operation_3209.definition: Compare the sequence or features of two or more genomes, for example, to find matching regions.

operation_3211.name: Genome indexing
operation_3211.definition:
Generate an index of a genome sequence.
Many sequence alignment tasks involving many or very large sequences rely on a precomputed index of the sequence to accelerate the alignment.  The Burrows-Wheeler Transform (BWT) is a permutation of the genome based on a suffix array algorithm.  A suffix array consists of the lexicographically sorted list of suffixes of a genome.

operation_3212.name: Genome indexing (Burrows-Wheeler)
operation_3212.definition:
Generate an index of a genome sequence using the Burrows-Wheeler algorithm.
The Burrows-Wheeler Transform (BWT) is a permutation of the genome based on a suffix array algorithm.

operation_3213.name: Genome indexing (suffix arrays)
operation_3213.definition:
Generate an index of a genome sequence using a suffix arrays algorithm.
A suffix array consists of the lexicographically sorted list of suffixes of a genome.

operation_3214.name: Spectral analysis
operation_3214.definition: Analyse one or more spectra from mass spectrometry (or other) experiments.

operation_3215.name: Peak detection
operation_3215.definition: Identify peaks in a spectrum from a mass spectrometry, NMR, or some other spectrum-generating experiment.

operation_3216.name: Scaffolding
operation_3216.definition:
Link together a non-contiguous series of genomic sequences into a scaffold, consisting of sequences separated by gaps of known length.  The sequences that are linked are typically typically contigs; contiguous sequences corresponding to read overlaps.
Scaffold may be positioned along a chromosome physical map to create a "golden path".

operation_3217.name: Scaffold gap completion
operation_3217.definition:
Fill the gaps in a sequence assembly (scaffold) by merging in additional sequences.
Different techniques are used to generate gap sequences to connect contigs, depending on the size of the gap. For small (5-20kb) gaps, PCR amplification and sequencing is used.  For large (>20kb) gaps, fragments are cloned (e.g. in BAC (Bacterial artificial chromosomes) vectors) and then sequenced.

operation_3218.name: Sequencing quality control
operation_3218.definition:
Raw sequence data quality control.
Analyse raw sequence data from a sequencing pipeline and identify (and possiby fix) problems.

operation_3219.name: Read pre-processing
operation_3219.definition:
Pre-process sequence reads to ensure (or improve) quality and reliability.
For example process paired end reads to trim low quality ends remove short sequences, identify sequence inserts, detect chimeric reads, or remove low quality sequnces including vector, adaptor, low complexity and contaminant sequences. Sequences might come from genomic DNA library, EST libraries, SSH library and so on.

operation_3221.name: Species frequency estimation
operation_3221.definition: Estimate the frequencies of different species from analysis of the molecular sequences, typically of DNA recovered from environmental samples.

operation_3222.name: Peak calling
operation_3222.definition:
Identify putative protein-binding regions in a genome sequence from analysis of Chip-sequencing data or ChIP-on-chip data.
Chip-sequencing combines chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP) with massively parallel DNA sequencing to generate a set of reads, which are aligned to a genome sequence.  The enriched areas contain the binding sites of DNA-associated proteins.  For example, a transcription factor binding site. ChIP-on-chip in contrast combines chromatin immunoprecipitation ('ChIP') with microarray ('chip').  "Peak-pair calling" is similar to "Peak calling" in the context of ChIP-exo.

operation_3223.name: Differential gene expression profiling
operation_3223.definition:
Identify from molecular sequence analysis (typically from analysis of microarray or RNA-seq data) genes whose expression levels are significantly different between two sample groups.
Differential gene expression analysis is used, for example, to identify which genes are up-regulated (increased expression) or down-regulated (decreased expression) between a group treated with a drug and a control groups.

operation_3224.name: Gene set testing
operation_3224.definition: Analyse gene expression patterns (typically from DNA microarray datasets) to identify sets of genes that are associated with a specific trait, condition, clinical outcome etc.

operation_3225.name: Variant classification
operation_3225.definition:
Classify variants based on their potential effect on genes, especially functional effects on the expressed proteins.
Variants are typically classified by their position (intronic, exonic, etc.) in a gene transcript and (for variants in coding exons) by their effect on the protein sequence (synonymous, non-synonymous, frameshifting, etc.)

operation_3226.name: Variant prioritisation
operation_3226.definition:
Identify biologically interesting variants by prioritizing individual variants, for example, homozygous variants absent in control genomes.
Variant prioritisation can be used for example to produce a list of variants responsible for 'knocking out' genes in specific genomes. Methods amino acid substitution, aggregative approaches, probabilistic approach, inheritance and unified likelihood-frameworks.

operation_3227.name: Variant calling
operation_3227.definition:
Detect, identify and map mutations, such as single nucleotide polymorphisms, short indels and structural variants, in multiple DNA sequences. Typically the alignment and comparison of the fluorescent traces produced by DNA sequencing hardware, to study genomic alterations.
Somatic variant calling is the detection of variations established in somatic cells and hence not inherited as a germ line variant.
Variant detection
Methods often utilise a database of aligned reads.

operation_3228.name: Structural variation detection
operation_3228.definition:
Detect large regions in a genome subject to copy-number variation, or other structural variations in genome(s).
Methods might involve analysis of whole-genome array comparative genome hybridisation or single-nucleotide polymorphism arrays, paired-end mapping of sequencing data, or from analysis of short reads from new sequencing technologies.

operation_3229.name: Exome assembly
operation_3229.definition: Analyse sequencing data from experiments aiming to selectively sequence the coding regions of the genome.

operation_3230.name: Read depth analysis
operation_3230.definition: Analyse mapping density (read depth) of (typically) short reads from sequencing platforms, for example, to detect deletions and duplications.

operation_3232.name: Gene expression QTL analysis
operation_3232.definition: Combine classical quantitative trait loci (QTL) analysis with gene expression profiling, for example, to describe describe cis- and trans-controlling elements for the expression of phenotype associated genes.
synonyms: Gene expression quantitative trait loci profiling

operation_3233.name: Copy number estimation
operation_3233.definition:
Estimate the number of copies of loci of particular gene(s) in DNA sequences typically from gene-expression profiling technology based on microarray hybridisation-based experiments. For example, estimate copy number (or marker dosage) of a dominant marker in samples from polyploid plant cells or tissues, or chromosomal gains and losses in tumors.
Methods typically implement some statistical model for hypothesis testing, and methods estimate total copy number, i.e. do not distinguish the two inherited chromosomes quantities (specific copy number).

operation_3237.name: Primer removal
operation_3237.definition: Remove forward and/or reverse primers from nucleic acid sequences (typically PCR products).

operation_3258.name: Transcriptome assembly
operation_3258.definition: Infer a transcriptome sequence by analysis of short sequence reads.

operation_3259.name: Transcriptome assembly (de novo)
operation_3259.definition: Infer a transcriptome sequence without the aid of a reference genome, i.e. by comparing short sequences (reads) to each other.

operation_3260.name: Transcriptome assembly (mapping)
operation_3260.definition: Infer a transcriptome sequence by mapping short reads to a reference genome.

operation_3267.name: Sequence coordinate conversion
operation_3267.definition: Convert one set of sequence coordinates to another, e.g. convert coordinates of one assembly to another, cDNA to genomic, CDS to genomic, protein translation to genomic etc.

operation_3278.name: Document similarity calculation
operation_3278.definition: Calculate similarity between 2 or more documents.

operation_3279.name: Document clustering
operation_3279.definition: Cluster (group) documents on the basis of their calculated similarity.

operation_3280.name: Named-entity and concept recognition
operation_3280.definition: Recognise named entities, ontology concepts, tags, events, and dictionary terms within documents.

operation_3282.name: ID mapping
operation_3282.definition:
Map data identifiers to one another for example to establish a link between two biological databases for the purposes of data integration.
The mapping can be achieved by comparing identifier values or some other means, e.g. exact matches to a provided sequence.

operation_3283.name: Anonymisation
operation_3283.definition: Process data in such a way that makes it hard to trace to the person which the data concerns.

operation_3289.name: ID retrieval
operation_3289.definition: Search for and retrieve a data identifier of some kind, e.g. a database entry accession.

operation_3348.name: Sequence checksum generation
operation_3348.definition: Generate a checksum of a molecular sequence.

operation_3349.name: Bibliography generation
operation_3349.definition: Construct a bibliography from the scientific literature.

operation_3350.name: Protein quaternary structure prediction
operation_3350.definition: Predict the structure of a multi-subunit protein and particularly how the subunits fit together.

operation_3351.name: Molecular surface analysis
operation_3351.definition: Analyse the surface properties of proteins or other macromolecules, including surface accessible pockets, interior inaccessible cavities etc.

operation_3352.name: Ontology comparison
operation_3352.definition: Compare two or more ontologies, e.g. identify differences.

operation_3353.name: Ontology comparison
operation_3353.definition: Compare two or more ontologies, e.g. identify differences.

operation_3357.name: Format detection
operation_3357.definition:
Recognition of which format the given data is in.
'Format recognition' is not a bioinformatics-specific operation, but of great relevance in bioinformatics. Should be removed from EDAM if/when captured satisfactorily in a suitable domain-generic ontology.

operation_3359.name: Splitting
operation_3359.definition: Split a file containing multiple data items into many files, each containing one item

operation_3429.name: Generation
operation_3429.definition:
Construct some data entity.
For non-analytical operations, see the 'Processing' branch.

operation_3430.name: Nucleic acid sequence feature detection
operation_3430.definition: Predict, recognise and identify functional or other key sites within nucleic acid sequences, typically by scanning for known motifs, patterns and regular expressions.

operation_3431.name: Deposition
operation_3431.definition:
Deposit some data in a database or some other type of repository or software system.
For non-analytical operations, see the 'Processing' branch.

operation_3432.name: Clustering
operation_3432.definition: Group together some data entities on the basis of similarities such that entities in the same group (cluster) are more similar to each other than to those in other groups (clusters).

operation_3433.name: Assembly
operation_3433.definition: Construct some entity (typically a molecule sequence) from component pieces.

operation_3434.name: Conversion
operation_3434.definition: Convert a data set from one form to another.

operation_3435.name: Standardisation and normalisation
operation_3435.definition:
Standardize or normalize data by some statistical method.
In the simplest normalisation means adjusting values measured on different scales to a common scale (often between 0.0 and 1.0), but can refer to more sophisticated adjustment whereby entire probability distributions of adjusted values are brought into alignment. Standardisation typically refers to an operation whereby a range of values are standardised to measure how many standard deviations a value is from its mean.

operation_3436.name: Aggregation
operation_3436.definition: Combine multiple files or data items into a single file or object.

operation_3437.name: Article comparison
operation_3437.definition: Compare two or more scientific articles.

operation_3438.name: Calculation
operation_3438.definition: Mathematical determination of the value of something, typically a properly of a  molecule.

operation_3439.name: Pathway or network prediction
operation_3439.definition: Predict a molecular pathway or network.

operation_3440.name: Genome assembly
operation_3440.definition: The process of assembling many short DNA sequences together such thay they represent the original chromosomes from which the DNA originated.

operation_3441.name: Plotting
operation_3441.definition: Generate a graph, or other visual representation, of data, showing the relationship between two or more variables.

operation_3443.name: Image analysis
operation_3443.definition: The analysis of a image (typically a digital image) of some type in order to extract information from it.

operation_3445.name: Diffraction data analysis
operation_3445.definition: Analysis of data from a diffraction experiment.

operation_3446.name: Cell migration analysis
operation_3446.definition: Analysis of cell migration images in order to study cell migration, typically in order to study the processes that play a role in the disease progression.

operation_3447.name: Diffraction data reduction
operation_3447.definition: Processing of diffraction data into a corrected, ordered, and simplified form.

operation_3450.name: Neurite measurement
operation_3450.definition: Measurement of neurites; projections (axons or dendrites) from the cell body of a neuron, from analysis of neuron images.

operation_3453.name: Diffraction data integration
operation_3453.definition: The evaluation of diffraction intensities and integration of diffraction maxima from a diffraction experiment.

operation_3454.name: Phasing
operation_3454.definition: Phase a macromolecular crystal structure, for example by using molecular replacement or experimental phasing methods.

operation_3455.name: Molecular replacement
operation_3455.definition:
A technique used to construct an atomic model of an unknown structure from diffraction data, based upon an atomic model of a known structure, either a related protein or the same protein from a different crystal form.
The technique solves the phase problem, i.e. retrieve information concern phases of the structure.

operation_3456.name: Rigid body refinement
operation_3456.definition:
A method used to refine a structure by moving the whole molecule or parts of it as a rigid unit, rather than moving individual atoms.
Rigid body refinement usually follows molecular replacement in the assignment of a structure from diffraction data.

operation_3457.name: Single particle analysis
operation_3457.definition:
An image processing technique that combines and analyze multiple images of a particulate sample, in order to produce an image with clearer features that are more easily interpreted.
Single particle analysis is used to improve the information that can be obtained by relatively low resolution techniques, , e.g. an image of a protein or virus from transmission electron microscopy (TEM).

operation_3458.name: Single particle alignment and classification
operation_3458.definition:
Compare (align and classify) multiple particle images from a micrograph in order to produce a representative image of the particle.
A micrograph can include particles in multiple different orientations and/or conformations. Particles are compared and organised into sets based on their similarity. Typically iterations of classification and alignment and are performed to optimise the final 3D EM map.

operation_3459.name: Functional clustering
operation_3459.definition: Clustering of molecular sequences on the basis of their function, typically using information from an ontology of gene function, or some other measure of functional phenotype.

operation_3460.name: Taxonomic classification
operation_3460.definition: Classifiication (typically of molecular sequences) by assignment to some taxonomic hierarchy.

operation_3461.name: Virulence prediction
operation_3461.definition: The prediction of the degree of pathogenicity of a microorganism from analysis of molecular sequences.

operation_3463.name: Expression correlation analysis
operation_3463.definition: Analyse the correlation patterns among features/molecules across across a variety of experiments, samples etc.

operation_3465.name: Correlation
operation_3465.definition: Identify a correlation, i.e. a statistical relationship between two random variables or two sets of data.

operation_3469.name: RNA structure covariance model generation
operation_3469.definition: Compute the covariance model for (a family of) RNA secondary structures.

operation_3470.name: RNA secondary structure prediction (shape-based)
operation_3470.definition: Predict RNA secondary structure by analysis, e.g. probabilistic analysis, of the shape of RNA folds.

operation_3471.name: Nucleic acid folding prediction (alignment-based)
operation_3471.definition: Prediction of nucleic-acid folding using sequence alignments as a source of data.

operation_3472.name: k-mer counting
operation_3472.definition:
Count k-mers (substrings of length k) in DNA sequence data.
k-mer counting is used in genome and transcriptome assembly, metagenomic sequencing, and for error correction of sequence reads.

operation_3478.name: Phylogenetic reconstruction
operation_3478.definition:
Reconstructing the inner node labels of a phylogenetic tree from its leafes.
Note that this is somewhat different from simply analysing an existing tree or constructing a completely new one.

operation_3480.name: Probabilistic data generation
operation_3480.definition: Generate some data from a choosen probibalistic model, possibly to evaluate algorithms.

operation_3481.name: Probabilistic sequence generation
operation_3481.definition: Generate sequences from some probabilistic model, e.g. a model that simulates evolution.

operation_3482.name: Antimicrobial resistance prediction
operation_3482.definition: Identify or predict causes for antibiotic resistance from molecular sequence analysis.

operation_3501.name: Enrichment analysis
operation_3501.definition:
Analysis of a set of objects, such as genes, annotated with given categories, where eventual over-/under-representation of certain categories within the studied set of objects is revealed.
Categories from a relevant ontology can be used. The input is typically a set of genes or other biological objects, possibly represented by their identifiers, and the output of the analysis is typically a ranked list of categories, each associated with a statistical metric of over-/under-representation within the studied data.

operation_3502.name: Chemical similarity enrichment
operation_3502.definition: Analyse a dataset with respect to concepts from an ontology of chemical structure, leveraging chemical similarity information.

operation_3503.name: Incident curve plotting
operation_3503.definition: Plot an incident curve such as a survival curve, death curve, mortality curve.

operation_3504.name: Variant pattern analysis
operation_3504.definition:
Identify and map patterns of genomic variations.
Methods often utilise a database of aligned reads.

operation_3545.name: Mathematical modelling
operation_3545.definition: Model some biological system using mathematical techniques including  dynamical systems, statistical models, differential equations, and game theoretic models.

operation_3552.name: Microscope image visualisation
operation_3552.definition: Visualise images resulting from various types of microscopy.

operation_3553.name: Image annotation
operation_3553.definition: Annotate an image of some sort, typically with terms from a controlled vocabulary.

operation_3557.name: Imputation
operation_3557.definition: Replace missing data with substituted values, usually by using some statistical or other mathematical approach.

operation_3559.name: Ontology visualisation
operation_3559.definition: Visualise, format or render data from an ontology, typically a tree of terms.

operation_3560.name: Maximum occurence analysis
operation_3560.definition: A method for making numerical assessments about the maximum percent of time that a conformer of a flexible macromolecule can exist and still be compatible with the experimental data.

operation_3561.name: Database comparison
operation_3561.definition: Compare the models or schemas used by two or more databases, or any other general comparison of databases rather than a detailed comparison of the entries themselves.

operation_3562.name: Network simulation
operation_3562.definition:
Simulate the bevaviour of a biological pathway or network.
Notions of pathway and network were mixed up, EDAM 1.24 disentangles them.

operation_3563.name: RNA-seq read count analysis
operation_3563.definition: Analyze read counts from RNA-seq experiments.

operation_3564.name: Chemical redundancy removal
operation_3564.definition: Identify and remove redudancy from a set of small molecule structures.

operation_3565.name: RNA-seq time series data analysis
operation_3565.definition: Analyze time series data from an RNA-seq experiment.

operation_3566.name: Simulated gene expression data generation
operation_3566.definition: Simulate gene expression data, e.g. for purposes of benchmarking.

operation_3625.name: Relation extraction
operation_3625.definition: Identify semantic relations among entities and concepts within a text, using text mining techniques.

operation_3627.name: Mass spectra calibration
operation_3627.definition: Re-adjust the output of mass spectrometry experiments with shifted ppm values.

operation_3628.name: Chromatographic alignment
operation_3628.definition: Align multiple data sets using information from chromatography and/or peptide identification, from mass spectrometry experiments.

operation_3629.name: Deisotoping
operation_3629.definition:
The removal of isotope peaks in a spectrum, to represent the fragment ion as one data point.
Deisotoping is commonly done to reduce complexity, and done in conjunction with the charge state deconvolution.

operation_3630.name: Protein quantification
operation_3630.definition: Technique for determining the amount of proteins in a sample.

operation_3631.name: Peptide identification
operation_3631.definition: Determination of peptide sequence from mass spectrum.

operation_3632.name: Isotopic distributions calculation
operation_3632.definition: Calculate the isotope distribution of a given chemical species.

operation_3633.name: Retention time prediction
operation_3633.definition: Prediction of retention time in a mass spectrometry experiment based on compositional and structural properties of the separated species.

operation_3634.name: Label-free quantification
operation_3634.definition: Quantification without the use of chemical tags.

operation_3635.name: Labeled quantification
operation_3635.definition: Quantification based on the use of chemical tags.

operation_3636.name: MRM/SRM
operation_3636.definition: Quantification by Selected/multiple Reaction Monitoring workflow (XIC quantitation of precursor / fragment mass pair).

operation_3637.name: Spectral counting
operation_3637.definition: Calculate number of identified MS2 spectra as approximation of peptide / protein quantity.

operation_3638.name: SILAC
operation_3638.definition: Quantification analysis using stable isotope labeling by amino acids in cell culture.

operation_3639.name: iTRAQ
operation_3639.definition: Quantification analysis using the AB SCIEX iTRAQ isobaric labelling workflow, wherein 2-8 reporter ions are measured in MS2 spectra near 114 m/z.

operation_3640.name: 18O labeling
operation_3640.definition: Quantification analysis using labeling based on 18O-enriched H2O.

operation_3641.name: TMT-tag
operation_3641.definition: Quantification analysis using the Thermo Fisher tandem mass tag labelling workflow.

operation_3642.name: Dimethyl
operation_3642.definition: Quantification analysis using chemical labeling by stable isotope dimethylation

operation_3643.name: Tag-based peptide identification
operation_3643.definition: Peptide sequence tags are used as piece of information about a peptide obtained by tandem mass spectrometry.

operation_3644.name: de Novo sequencing
operation_3644.definition: Analytical process that derives a peptide's amino acid sequence from its tandem mass spectrum (MS/MS) without the assistance of a sequence database.

operation_3645.name: PTM identification
operation_3645.definition: Identification of post-translational modifications (PTMs) of peptides/proteins in mass spectrum.

operation_3646.name: Peptide database search
operation_3646.definition: Determination of best matches between MS/MS spectrum and a database of protein or nucleic acid sequences.

operation_3647.name: Blind peptide database search
operation_3647.definition: Peptide database search for identification of known and unknown PTMs looking for mass difference mismatches.

operation_3648.name: Validation of peptide-spectrum matches
operation_3648.definition: Statistical estimation of false discovery rate from score distribution for peptide-spectrum-matches, following a peptide database search.

operation_3649.name: Target-Decoy
operation_3649.definition: Statistical estimation of false discovery rate from score distribution for peptide-spectrum-matches, following a peptide database search, and by comparison to search results with a database containing incorrect information.

operation_3658.name: Statistical inference
operation_3658.definition: Analyse data in order to deduce properties of an underlying distribution or population.

operation_3659.name: Regression analysis
operation_3659.definition: A statistical calculation to estimate the relationships among variables.

operation_3660.name: Metabolic network modelling
operation_3660.definition:
Model a metabolic network.  This can include 1) reconstruction to break down a metabolic pathways into reactions, enzymes, and other relevant information, and compilation of this into a mathematical model and 2) simulations of metabolism based on the model.
The terms and synyonyms here reflect that for practical intents and purposes, "pathway" and "network" can be treated the same.

operation_3661.name: SNP annotation
operation_3661.definition: Predict the effect or function of an individual single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP).

operation_3662.name: Ab-initio gene prediction
operation_3662.definition: Prediction of genes or gene components from first principles, i.e. without reference to existing genes.

operation_3663.name: Homology-based gene prediction
operation_3663.definition: Prediction of genes or gene components by reference to homologous genes.

operation_3664.name: Statistical modelling
operation_3664.definition: Construction of a statistical model, or a set of assumptions around some observed data, usually by describing a set of probability distributions which approximate the distribution of data.

operation_3666.name: Molecular surface comparison
operation_3666.definition: Compare two or more molecular surfaces.

operation_3672.name: Gene functional annotation
operation_3672.definition: Annotate one or more sequences with functional information, such as cellular processes or metaobolic pathways, by reference to a controlled vocabulary - invariably the Gene Ontology (GO).

operation_3675.name: Variant filtering
operation_3675.definition: Variant filtering is used to eliminate false positive variants based for example on base calling quality, strand and position information, and mapping info.

operation_3677.name: Differential binding analysis
operation_3677.definition: Identify binding sites in nucleic acid sequences that are statistically significantly differentially bound between sample groups.

operation_3694.name: Mass spectrum visualisation
operation_3694.definition: Visualise, format or render a mass spectrum.

operation_3695.name: Filtering
operation_3695.definition: Filter a set of files or data items according to some property.

operation_3703.name: Reference identification
operation_3703.definition: Identification of the best reference for mapping for a specific dataset from a list of potential references, when performing genetic variation analysis.

operation_3704.name: Ion counting
operation_3704.definition: Label-free quantification by integration of ion current (ion counting).

operation_3705.name: Isotope-coded protein label
operation_3705.definition: Chemical tagging free amino groups of intact proteins with stable isotopes.

operation_3715.name: Metabolic labeling
operation_3715.definition:
Labeling all proteins and (possibly) all amino acids using C-13 or N-15 enriched grown medium or feed.
This includes N-15 metabolic labeling (labeling all proteins and (possibly) all amino acids using N-15 enriched grown medium or feed) and C-13 metabolic labeling (labeling all proteins and (possibly) all amino acids using C-13 enriched grown medium or feed).

operation_3730.name: Cross-assembly
operation_3730.definition: Construction of a single sequence assembly of all reads from different samples, typically as part of a comparative metagenomic analysis.

operation_3731.name: Sample comparison
operation_3731.definition: The comparison of samples from a metagenomics study, for example, by comparison of metagenome shotgun reads or assembled contig sequences, by comparison of functional profiles, or some other method.

operation_3741.name: Differential protein expression profiling
operation_3741.definition: The analysis, using proteomics techniques, to identify proteins whose encoding genes are differentially expressed under a given experimental setup.

operation_3742.name: Differential gene expression analysis
operation_3742.definition: The analysis, using any of diverse techniques, to identify genes that are differentially expressed under a given experimental setup.

operation_3744.name: Multiple sample visualisation
operation_3744.definition: Visualise, format or render data arising from an analysis of multiple samples from a metagenomics/community experiment.

operation_3745.name: Ancestral reconstruction
operation_3745.definition:
The extrapolation of empirical characteristics of individuals or populations, backwards in time, to their common ancestors.
Ancestral reconstruction is often used to recover possible ancestral character states of ancient, extinct organisms.

operation_3755.name: PTM localisation
operation_3755.definition: Site localisation of post-translational modifications in peptide or protein mass spectra.

operation_3760.name: Service management
operation_3760.definition: Operations concerning the handling and use of other tools.

operation_3761.name: Service discovery
operation_3761.definition: An operation supporting the browsing or discovery of other tools and services.

operation_3762.name: Service composition
operation_3762.definition: An operation supporting the aggregation of other services (at least two) into a funtional unit, for the automation of some task.

operation_3763.name: Service invocation
operation_3763.definition: An operation supporting the calling (invocation) of other tools and services.

operation_3766.name: Weighted correlation network analysis
operation_3766.definition: A data mining method typically used for studying biological networks based on pairwise correlations between variables.

operation_3767.name: Protein identification
operation_3767.definition: Identification of protein, for example from one or more peptide identifications by tandem mass spectrometry.

operation_3778.name: Text annotation
operation_3778.definition: Text annotation is the operation of adding notes, data and metadata, recognised entities and concepts, and their relations to a text (such as a scientific article).

operation_3791.name: Collapsing methods
operation_3791.definition:
A method whereby data on several variants are "collapsed" into a single covariate based on regions such as genes.
Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) analyse a genome-wide set of genetic variants in different individuals to see if any variant is associated with a trait. Traditional association techniques can lack the power to detect the significance of rare variants individually, or measure their compound effect (rare variant burden).  "Collapsing methods" were developed to overcome these problems.

operation_3792.name: miRNA expression analysis
operation_3792.definition: The analysis of microRNAs (miRNAs) : short, highly conserved small noncoding RNA molecules that are naturally occurring plant and animal genomes.

operation_3793.name: Read summarisation
operation_3793.definition: Counting and summarising the number of short sequence reads that map to genomic features.

operation_3795.name: In vitro selection
operation_3795.definition: A technique whereby molecules with desired properties and function are isolated from libraries of random molecules, through iterative cycles of selection, amplification, and mutagenesis.

operation_3797.name: Rarefaction
operation_3797.definition: The calculation of species richness for a number of individual samples, based on plots of the number of species as a function of the number of samples (rarefaction curves).

operation_3798.name: Read binning
operation_3798.definition:
An operation which groups reads or contigs and assigns them to operational taxonomic units.
Binning methods use one or a combination of compositional features or sequence similarity.

operation_3799.name: Quantification
operation_3799.definition: Counting and measuring experimentally determined observations into quantities.

operation_3800.name: RNA-Seq quantification
operation_3800.definition: Quantification of data arising from RNA-Seq high-throughput sequencing, typically the quantification of transcript abundances durnig transcriptome analysis in a gene expression study.

operation_3801.name: Spectral library search
operation_3801.definition: Match experimentally measured mass spectrum to a spectrum in a spectral library or database.

operation_3802.name: Sorting
operation_3802.definition: Sort a set of files or data items according to some property.

operation_3803.name: Natural product identification
operation_3803.definition: Mass spectra identification of compounds that are produced by living systems. Including polyketides, terpenoids, phenylpropanoids, alkaloids and antibiotics.

operation_3809.name: DMR identification
operation_3809.definition: Identify and assess specific genes or regulatory regions of interest that are differentially methylated.

operation_3840.name: Multilocus sequence typing
operation_3840.definition: Genotyping of multiple loci, typically characterizing microbial species isolates using internal fragments of multiple housekeeping genes.

operation_3860.name: Spectrum calculation
operation_3860.definition: Calculate a theoretical mass spectrometry spectra for given sequences.

operation_3891.name: Essential dynamics
operation_3891.definition:
Compute Essential Dynamics (ED) on a simulation trajectory: an analysis of molecule dynamics using PCA (Principal Component Analysis) applied to the atomic positional fluctuations.
Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a multivariate statistical analysis to obtain collective variables and reduce the dimensionality of the system.

operation_3893.name: Forcefield parameterisation
operation_3893.definition: Obtain force field parameters (charge, bonds, dihedrals, etc.) from a molecule, to be used in molecular simulations

operation_3894.name: DNA profiling
operation_3894.definition: Analyse DNA sequences in order to determine an individual's DNA characteristics, for example in criminal forensics, parentage testing and so on.

operation_3896.name: Active site prediction
operation_3896.definition: Predict or detect active sites in proteins; the region of an enzyme which binds a substrate bind and catalyses a reaction.

operation_3897.name: Ligand-binding site prediction
operation_3897.definition: Predict or detect ligand-binding sites in proteins; a region of a protein which reversibly binds a ligand for some biochemical purpose, such as transport or regulation of protein function.

operation_3898.name: Metal-binding site prediction
operation_3898.definition: Predict or detect metal ion-binding sites in proteins.

operation_3899.name: Protein-protein docking
